        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>People Also Ask (PAA)</strong> is a Google SERP feature that displays expandable question boxes with short answers extracted from web pages. It appears in approximately 65% of all Google searches (Ahrefs, 2023) and typically shows 4 initial questions that expand dynamically as users interact — creating dozens of visibility opportunities beyond standard organic rankings.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">SERP presence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">65% of queries</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">SERP Features</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Source ranking</div>
            <div class="tms-value">74% outside top 3</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">PAA is one of the most underexploited SEO opportunities available. Most teams focus on ranking in the top 3 organic positions. PAA lets a page ranked #8 appear above position #1 — getting above-the-fold visibility on a query it would otherwise miss entirely.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is People Also Ask (PAA)?</h2>
        <p>PAA is a dynamic question-and-answer box that Google displays within organic search results. Unlike a featured snippet (which answers the search query itself), PAA answers related questions that users commonly ask about the same topic. Clicking any question expands it to reveal a short answer, the source URL, and 2–3 additional questions — which expand infinitely the more a user interacts.</p>
        <p>Google draws PAA answers from its existing index. A page does not need to be ranking in the top 3, or even on page 1, to appear in PAA. The selection criteria prioritize clarity of the answer over ranking position — which is why 74% of PAA results come from pages outside the top 3 organic results.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Ahrefs 2023 research</div>
          <p>Ahrefs' analysis of millions of search queries found that <strong>65% of all Google searches show a PAA box</strong>. For informational queries (how-to, what-is, why), the percentage is even higher. PAA is now the most common SERP feature after sitelinks.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why People Also Ask matters for SEO</h2>
        <p>PAA creates four distinct advantages over standard organic optimization:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Visibility without top-3 rankings.</strong> A page ranking #8 can appear in a PAA box above organic position #1. This is above-the-fold real estate for queries where you would otherwise be invisible to most users.</li>
          <li><strong>Infinite question expansion.</strong> Each PAA interaction generates 2–3 new related questions. A single well-structured page can appear across dozens of related queries as users expand the box and trigger new question sets.</li>
          <li><strong>Connection to AI Overviews.</strong> Google's AI Overviews source content from the same pool as PAA. Pages optimized for PAA inclusion are significantly more likely to be cited in AI Overview answers for the same queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Cumulative traffic from question clusters.</strong> PAA clicks represent 3–5% of total SERP clicks on queries with PAA boxes. Across dozens of queries where a page appears in PAA, this adds up — one B2B SaaS company found 18% of its organic traffic came from PAA appearances alone.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How People Also Ask works</h2>
        <p>Google's PAA system operates through three distinct mechanisms:</p>

        <h3>Question generation</h3>
        <p>Google identifies questions using patterns from billions of previous searches. If users who searched "what is SEO" frequently follow up with "how long does SEO take" and "is SEO worth it," those follow-up queries become PAA question candidates for "what is SEO" searches.</p>

        <h3>Answer extraction</h3>
        <p>For each question, Google scans its index for pages that answer clearly. The extraction algorithm favors:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Pages with the question in an H2 or H3 heading</li>
          <li>Direct answers in the first sentence below the heading (40–60 words)</li>
          <li>Strong E-E-A-T signals (experience, expertise, authoritativeness, trustworthiness)</li>
          <li>Structured HTML (ordered lists, tables, clear paragraphs)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Dynamic expansion</h3>
        <p>PAA boxes start with 4 questions. Each click on a question adds 2–3 contextually related questions. This creates a branching tree of question-answer pairs — meaning a single query can eventually surface PAA results from hundreds of different pages as a user digs deeper.</p>

