        <h2 id="examples">Real PAA optimization examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Dental practice: PAA above organic position #6</h3>
        <p>A Chicago dental practice published "How Much Do Dental Implants Cost in Chicago?" — ranking #6 organically for the main keyword. The page had a clear H2 for the cost question with a direct answer in the first sentence. The PAA box for related implant queries began sourcing from this page, putting it above-the-fold on queries where it ranked #6 — driving more clicks than its organic position suggested possible.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B SaaS: 43 PAA queries from one article</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS company publishing 30 in-depth articles monthly found that one 3,200-word article appeared in 43 different PAA question boxes. PAA clicks from those 43 questions accounted for 18% of the article's total organic traffic — all from a page not ranking in the top 3 for most of those queries.</p>

        <h3>3. Blog failing PAA despite good rankings</h3>
        <p>A blog with quality content but poor structure failed PAA inclusion despite ranking positions 2–5 for competitive queries. The articles lacked question-format headings and did not open sections with direct answers. After restructuring to add H2 questions and 40-word direct answers, PAA appearances increased across the site within 6 weeks.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">People Also Ask vs. Featured Snippets — which to prioritize?</h2>

