                <td><strong>Source ranking required</strong></td>
                <td>Any position (even page 2)</td>
                <td>Usually top 10</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Visibility</strong></td>
                <td>Moderate (requires click to expand)</td>
                <td>High (immediately visible)</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Multiple appearances</strong></td>
                <td>Same page across many questions</td>
                <td>One page, one snippet per query</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Difficulty to win</strong></td>
                <td>Lower — less competition per question</td>
                <td>Higher — one winner per query</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>The practical answer: optimize for both simultaneously. The same technique — question-format headings + direct 40-60 word answers — wins both PAA and featured snippets. PAA gives you more opportunities; featured snippets give you higher individual visibility.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for winning People Also Ask</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Research actual PAA questions before writing.</strong> Search your target keyword, note the PAA questions Google shows, and write content that directly answers them. Use AlsoAsked.com or Semrush's PAA tool to map question clusters before outlining.</li>
          <li><strong>Use question-format H2 or H3 headings.</strong> "How do I get into People Also Ask?" as an H2, not "Getting into PAA." The heading structure signals to Google that this section answers a specific question.</li>
          <li><strong>Answer in 40–60 words in the first sentence.</strong> Google extracts the opening of the section. The direct answer must appear immediately — not after two sentences of context. Answer first, then elaborate.</li>
          <li><strong>Add FAQ sections to every article.</strong> FAQ sections create multiple question-answer pairs on a single page, each independently eligible for PAA inclusion. 3–5 FAQ questions per article multiplies your PAA surface area significantly.</li>
          <li><strong>Target question clusters, not single questions.</strong> Write one article that answers 8–10 related questions rather than 8–10 thin articles answering one question each. PAA expansion logic rewards pages that answer follow-up questions users naturally ask next.</li>
          <li><strong>Use FAQPage schema markup.</strong> Google explicitly uses FAQPage schema when generating PAA answers. Mark up your FAQ sections with structured data — it increases the likelihood your answers are extracted and cited.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — burying the answer</div>
          <p>The most common PAA optimization failure is starting an answer with context before the actual answer. "Great question — there are many factors to consider..." followed by 3 sentences before the real answer means Google sees 60 words of preamble, not a direct answer. Put the answer in sentence 1. Context goes after.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common PAA mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Writing statements as headings instead of questions</strong> — "PAA traffic statistics" as an H2 won't be recognized as answering a question. "How much traffic does PAA drive?" will.</li>
          <li><strong>Answers longer than 80 words in the opening</strong> — Google extracts short, complete answers. A 200-word opening paragraph won't be extracted cleanly.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring question research before writing</strong> — guessing what PAA questions exist misses the actual language users search. Research first, write second.</li>
          <li><strong>Focusing only on your primary keyword's PAA</strong> — PAA expansion means related questions from adjacent queries can surface your page. Map the full question cluster around your topic, not just the head term.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing FAQPage schema markup</strong> — adding the schema costs 15 minutes and meaningfully increases PAA extraction rates. Not adding it is a missed optimization.</li>
        </ul>

